Data Processing

The first step is to read in one section fo the data using the following code:

# Read in the data
library(tidyverse)
library(readr)
sheet1 = read_csv("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01a.csv")

In order to finish step 1, we use select function to select the variables, then rename the variable.

# Step 1
sheet1_selected = select(as_tibble(sheet1),Area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D"))
colnames(sheet1_selected)[1] = "area_name"

Next, we use pivot_longer function to change the data to long format.

# Step 2
sheet1_long = pivot_longer(sheet1_selected, cols = 3:12, names_to = "ID", values_to = "enrollment_value")

Since we do not know how may years are recorded, we assume value less than 30 are from 21th century and values that are 30 and above are from the 20th century. By simply change the data type to numeric, and add the century years (1900 or 2000), we can add the year variable accordingly.

# Step 3
year = as.numeric(substr(sheet1_long$ID, 8,9))

for (i in 1:length(year)) {
  if (year[i]<30) {year[i] = year[i]+2000} else {year[i] = year[i]+1900}
}

grab = substr(sheet1_long$ID, 1,7)

sheet1_with_year_grab = cbind(sheet1_long,year, grab)

Use the provided code to identify the index for county dataset. Then find the complementary index to establish the dataset state.

# Step 4
sheet1_county = as_tibble(sheet1_with_year_grab[grep(pattern = ", \\w\\w", sheet1_with_year_grab$area_name),])

index = subset(1:nrow(sheet1_with_year_grab), !(1:nrow(sheet1_with_year_grab) %in% grep(pattern = ", \\w\\w", sheet1_with_year_grab$area_name)))
sheet1_state = as_tibble(sheet1_with_year_grab[index,])

# class to the tibble
class(sheet1_county) = c("county", class(sheet1_county))
class(sheet1_state)  = c("state", class(sheet1_state))

# Step 5
sheet1_county = mutate(sheet1_county,state = substr(sheet1_county$area_name,(nchar(sheet1_county$area_name) - 1), nchar(sheet1_county$area_name)))

Separate Functions

Making the corresponding functions just need to change the global variables to local function-based variables.

sheet2 = read_csv("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01b.csv")

# Function for step 1&2
fun1 = function(dat,value = "enrollment_value") {
  dat_selected = select(as_tibble(dat),Area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D"))
  colnames(dat_selected)[1] = "area_name"
  dat_long = pivot_longer(dat_selected, cols = 3:12, names_to = "ID", values_to = value)
  return(dat_long)
}

# Function for step 3
fun2 = function(dat) {
  year = as.numeric(substr(dat$ID, 8,9))
  for (i in 1:length(year)) {
  if (year[i]<30) {year[i] = year[i]+2000} else {year[i] = year[i]+1900}
  }
  grab = substr(dat$ID, 1,7)
  dat_with_year_grab = cbind(dat,year,grab)
  return(dat_with_year_grab)
}

# Function for step 5
fun3 = function(dat) {
  dat_new = mutate(dat,state = substr(dat$area_name,(nchar(dat$area_name) - 1), nchar(dat$area_name)))
  return(dat_new)
  }

# Function for step 6
fun4 = function(dat) {
  D1 = tolower(c("Connecticut", "Maine", "Massachusetts", "New Hampshire", "Rhode Island", "Vermont"))
  D2 = tolower(c("New Jersey", "New York", "Pennsylvania"))
  D3 = tolower(c("Illinois", "Indiana", "Michigan", "Ohio", "Wisconsin"))
  D4 = tolower(c("Iowa", "Kansas", "Minnesota", "Missouri", "Nebraska", "North Dakota", "South Dakota"))
  D5 = tolower(c("Delaware", "Florida", "Georgia", "Maryland", "North Carolina", "South Carolina", "Virginia", "District of Columbia", "West Virginia"))
  D6 = tolower(c("Alabama", "Kentucky", "Mississippi", "Tennessee"))
  D7 = tolower(c("Arkansas", "Louisiana", "Oklahoma", "Texas"))
  D8 = tolower(c("Arizona", "Colorado", "Idaho", "Montana", "Nevada", "New Mexico", "Utah", "Wyoming"))
  D9 = tolower(c("Alaska", "California", "Hawaii", "Oregon", "Washington"))
  
  division = c()
  
  for (i in 1:nrow(dat)) {
  if (tolower(dat$area_name[i]) %in% D1) {
    division[i]="division 1"
  } else if (tolower(dat$area_name[i]) %in% D2) {
      division[i]="division 2"
  } else if (tolower(dat$area_name[i]) %in% D3) {
        division[i]="division 3"
  } else if (tolower(dat$area_name[i]) %in% D4) {
          division[i]="division 4"
  } else if (tolower(dat$area_name[i]) %in% D5) {
            division[i]="division 5"
  } else if (tolower(dat$area_name[i]) %in% D6) {
              division[i]="division 6"
  } else if (tolower(dat$area_name[i]) %in% D7) {
                division[i]="division 7"
  } else if (tolower(dat$area_name[i]) %in% D8) {
                  division[i]="division 8"
  } else if (tolower(dat$area_name[i]) %in% D9) {
                    division[i]="division 9"
  } else {
                      division[i]="ERROR"
         }
  }
  
  dat = mutate(dat, division)
  
  return(dat)
}

# Function for step 4
## Can only use list to return both tibbles
fun5 = function(dat) {
  county = as_tibble(dat[grep(pattern = ", \\w\\w", dat$area_name),])
  
  index = subset(1:nrow(dat), !(1:nrow(dat) %in% grep(pattern = ", \\w\\w", dat$area_name)))
  state = as_tibble(dat[index,])
  
  county_out = fun3(county)
  state_out = fun4(state)
  
  class(county_out) = c("county", class(county_out))
  class(state_out)  = c("state", class(state_out))
  
  return(list(county_out, state_out))
}

Functions in the wrap up function needs to take the corresponding inputs from previous functions by carefully arrange the local variables.

# Wrap the functions
my_wrapper = function(url, value = "enrollment_value") {
  a = read_csv(url)
  b = fun1(a, value)
  c = fun2(b)
  d = fun5(c)
  
  return(d)
}

fun6 = function(result1, result2) {
  bind_county = bind_rows(list(result1[1],result2[1]))
  bind_state = bind_rows(list(result1[2],result2[2]))
  bind  = list(bind_county,bind_state)
  return(bind)
}

bind = fun6(sheet1_result,sheet2_result)

Write a Generic Function for Summarizing

Write a plot function which specified the class type for plot. For state class, plot by years and colored by divisions. For county class, identify the state to be selected, calculate the mean, obtain the top/bottom values, then use the area_name to filter the original dataset and obtain the actual statistics.

plot.state <- function(df){
  state_plot = df %>% group_by(year,division) %>% summarise(mean = mean(get("enrollment_value")))
  state_plot = state_plot[!(state_plot$division == "ERROR"),]

  ggplot(state_plot, aes(x = state_plot$year, y = state_plot$mean, color = division)) + geom_line()
}


plot.county = function(df, state = "AL", specify = "top", number = 5) {
  state_only = df[(df$state == state),]
  
  sort_mean = state_only %>% group_by(area_name) %>% summarise(mean = mean(get("enrollment_value")))
  if (specify =="top") {
    sort_mean = arrange(sort_mean,desc(mean))
  } else if (specify =="bottom") {
      sort_mean = arrange(sort_mean,mean)
  } else {
      print("error")
    }
  
  top_bottum = sort_mean[1:number,]
  
  filter = filter(state_only, area_name %in% top_bottum$area_name)
  
  ggplot(filter, aes(x = year, y = get("enrollment_value"), color = area_name)) +
geom_line()
}
